          "explanation": "Vectors in Two Dimensions A vector is a quantity that has magnitude and direction. Displacement, velocity, acceleration, and force, for example, are all vectors. In one-dimensional, or straight-line, motion, the direction of a vector can be given simply by a plus or minus sign. In two dimensions (2-d), however, we specify the direction of a vector relative to some reference frame (i. , coordinate system), using an arrow having length proportional to the vector’s magnitude and pointing in the direction of the vector. Figure 3.9 shows such a graphical representation of a vector, using as an exam..."
